						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/Commodities/Livestock/Related-developments/The-assumption-that-a-cow-needs-a-higher-energy-intake-before-calving-challenged" title="The assumption that a cow needs a higher energy intake before calving challenged    " alt="link">The assumption that a cow needs a higher energy intake before calving challenged    </a></h2>

	
					<p>Animal sciences researcher Phil Cardoso and colleagues at the University of Illinois College of Agricultural, Consumer and Environmental Sciences (ACES), conducted &nbsp;an experiment to compare cows fed before calving with diets containing the recommended energy levels (of the US regime) to cows fed only 80% of the recommended &nbsp;energy amount. They found that the cows fed the reduced energy diets performed better reproductively after calving, becoming pregnant about 10 days sooner that cows &nbsp;enjoying the high-energy diet. &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<a href="http://www.alphagalileo.org/ViewItem.aspx?ItemId=133665&amp;CultureCode=en" target="_self">http://www.alphagalileo.org/ViewItem.aspx?ItemId=133665&amp;CultureCode=en</a>&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;(AlphaGalileo, 14/08/2013) &nbsp;</p>
							<p><span class="date">20/09/2013</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/Commodities/Livestock/Related-developments/The-assumption-that-a-cow-needs-a-higher-energy-intake-before-calving-challenged">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/Commodities/Livestock/Related-developments/Omega-3-in-dairy-down-to-the-antimicrobial-effects-of-green-odour-compounds-from-grass" title="Omega-3 in dairy down to the antimicrobial effects of 'green odour' compounds from grass   " alt="link">Omega-3 in dairy down to the antimicrobial effects of 'green odour' compounds from grass   </a></h2>

	
					<p>Scientists at the BBSRC Institute of Biological, Environmental and Rural Sciences (IBERS, UK) discovered that the molecules that give cut grass its distinctive 'green odour' kill off bacteria that convert healthy omega-3 fats into saturated fats in a &nbsp;cow's gut. Milk contains a greater proportion of the healthy omega-3 fats in the summer than in the winter due most probably to the antimicrobial effects of the green odour compound from grass. &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<a href="http://www.bbsrc.ac.uk/news/food-security/2013/130821-pr-cut-grass-smell-is-key.aspx" target="_self">http://www.bbsrc.ac.uk/news/food-security/2013/130821-pr-cut-grass-smell-is-key.aspx</a>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;(BBSRC, 21/08/2013)&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;</p>
							<p><span class="date">18/09/2013</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/Commodities/Livestock/Related-developments/Omega-3-in-dairy-down-to-the-antimicrobial-effects-of-green-odour-compounds-from-grass">Read more...</a>
